      "writtenOn": "2017-11-17T17:09:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "i believe integer ids will complicate the application down the road. They already cause some unnecessary complexity here. Let me explain.\n\nseparation of id and name is valuable when there is a need to rename entities, so that we don\u0027t have to update all the related rows in different tables. Do datacenters get renamed though? I am not sure about this requirement. Even if they were, our configs do not specify ids, so on a rename attempt, this function will try to delete exiting datacenter, either fail or delete all of its descendants and create a new empty datacenter\n\nlater, our RPCs have filters by datacenter names, not ids. It means we will have to either write a JOIN for each reference property (router, datacenter, machine, etc) for each entity type containing the property, or we will have to run a query to retrieve ids of datacenter and then make actual search query.\n\nboth kinds of complexities can be mitigated if names are primary keys, or rather rename \"name\" fields in all config entities to \"id\" use it as a primary key",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 61,
        "startChar": 31,
        "endLine": 61,
        "endChar": 35
      },
      "revId": "4ac64e9835cdc5fa6b35137797a21dd99ad2254e",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3cf330d5_5e2a927a",
        "filename": "machine-db/appengine/model/datacenters/datacenters.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 61,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003211
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-11-18T00:56:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Good point, you\u0027re right that datacenters can\u0027t be renamed, but I didn\u0027t want it to be impossible. I\u0027m also trying to keep things consistent with auto-generated IDs used everywhere in case we can\u0027t rely on name uniqueness. With hosts, for example, the primary key would need to be (name, vlan_id) which makes it complicated to reference a host (IP addresses table will need to reference hosts). I am also purposely trying to avoid any extra validation in the database and keep it all in the app, which means that right now in the schema names are not required to be unique. This is also consistent with reality, for example we have agreed to keep things like rack and switch names globally unique but in theory they only need to be unique per datacenter. int is also smaller than varchar(255) once the string reaches 4 characters in length, but this is a lesser concern.",
      "parentUuid": "38321e33_9ccddac2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 61,
        "startChar": 31,
        "endLine": 61,
        "endChar": 35
      },
